          "body": "Verse 7 names the fathers who sinned and are no more, while the present generation bears their iniquities. This has been a stumbling block for readers — it appears to contradict individual accountability (Ezekiel 18:20; Deuteronomy 24:16). But the tension is more complex. The present generation is not claiming total innocence — verse 16 owns the sin in the first person plural: 'we have sinned.' What verse 7 describes is the covenantal solidarity of sin's consequences across time: communities are not isolated individuals, and covenant rebellion has multi-generational consequences (Exodus 20:5-6). John Calvin's note is apt: the children were not unjustly punished for their fathers' sins alone, but were themselves participants in the rebellion that ripened across generations. The chapter refuses both total self-exoneration (blaming the fathers entirely) and total self-flagellation (ignoring the generational dimension). Both are true. This is the most mature treatment of sin in the book."
