          "title": "The theological pivot — God's throne against the ruins of Zion (vv. 18-19)",
          "body": "The chapter's most remarkable juxtaposition is the pairing of verses 18 and 19. Verse 18 names the nadir: Mount Zion lies desolate, foxes prowl it. The holy hill — the dwelling-place of Yahweh's name, the site of the Ark and the temple, the center of all covenant worship — is now animal territory. D. A. Carson's observation about Lamentations is precise: the poet is not trying to make the desolation comfortable; he is making it as stark as possible so that the turn to God's sovereignty in verse 19 carries full weight. 'But You, O LORD, rule forever; Your throne is from generation to generation.' Every human throne has been overturned — princes hung by their hands (v. 12), the crown fallen (v. 16). Only one throne remains. This is the chapter's sole theological anchor, and the entire petition of verses 20-21 hangs on it. The argument is: if Your throne endures from generation to generation, then Your apparent abandonment (v. 20) cannot be Your final word."
